<div id="review_1287351387" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1287351387" />
    <a title="David M" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43332343-david-m"><img alt="David M" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1570428545p2/43332343.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1287351387?book_show_action=true">May 22, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David M" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David M" href="/user/show/43332343-david-m">David M</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1287351387" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16703110414682919407">6/16/20 - happy Bloomsday; I continue to reread my favorite books in quarantine, the prison of health (حجر صحي). Suttree is one of the greatest ever. This time as I read I kept imagining the prequel, the story of Sut&apos;s disastrous marriage. The sequel remains unimaginable. The book itself seems to be deliberately set during the most uneventful (and wretched) period of the man&apos;s life. When he&apos;s not even a hobo, he&apos;s just a bum. <br/><br/>***<br/>&apos;You have no right to represent people this way, he said. A man is </span>
  <span id="freeText16703110414682919407" style="display:none">6/16/20 - happy Bloomsday; I continue to reread my favorite books in quarantine, the prison of health (حجر صحي). Suttree is one of the greatest ever. This time as I read I kept imagining the prequel, the story of Sut's disastrous marriage. The sequel remains unimaginable. The book itself seems to be deliberately set during the most uneventful (and wretched) period of the man's life. When he's not even a hobo, he's just a bum. <br /><br />***<br />'You have no right to represent people this way, he said. A man is all men. You have no right to your wretchedness' (422)<br /><br />Here Suttree is speaking to the corpse of an old homeless man, but of course he's also addressing himself. How wretched does a person have a right to be? In this book we don't find the usual trappings of human dignity. There's very little of the normative ought. People just do what they do. This passage, coming near the end, is a rare lapse, a case of self-reflection. But then of course the questions that can be raised have no answers, no solution to being human. <br /><br />'In and through man desires advance masked' - Paul Ricoeur, Freud and Philosophy<br /><br />The id as the ever prior. To try and narrate dreams during the day is inevitably to do them violence. Be that as it may, occasionally one encounters a work of art which appears like a direct expression of the inexpressible. For me Suttree is exactly that. Once James Wood complained that McCarthy's novels simply erase mind. This may be justified regarding his westerns and later books, but I don't think it's true of Suttree. Perhaps because the material comes so much from the author's own life and experiences, here subjectivity is not entirely denied. Style instead becomes the fusion of inner and outer. <br /><br />I'm happy to end 2015 by rereading one of my favorites. If anything I'm more in awe of this book now than when I first encountered it two years ago. Before reading it I had no idea a book like this even existed. I'd always wanted to read a great American novel about bums and derelicts, and didn't know one already existed. But here it is in all its glory. I want to just drop the qualifiers and say it's one of the greatest novels of the past hundred years.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16703110414682919407" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


